messages.content:
THOUGHT

ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:23` frees `b->name` on the recoverable parse-error path but leaves `b->name` still pointing at the freed allocation. `load_blob()` then returns this partially initialized `blob_t` to the caller with `size == 0`. Later, `main()` calls `destroy_blob(b)`, and `destroy_blob()` unconditionally calls `free(b->name)` at `program.c:33`. Because the pointer value was not cleared or ownership was not otherwise transferred/invalidated after the first `free`, the destructor frees the same allocation a second time. ASan confirms: allocation at line 15, first free at line 23, second free at line 33.

LOCAL FIX: After freeing `b->name` in the recoverable error path, set it to `NULL` so the returned object remains in a destructor-safe state. `free(NULL)` is a no-op, so `destroy_blob()` can stay unchanged.
```diff
--- a/program.c
+++ b/program.c
@@ -20,8 +20,9 @@ static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {
     }
     /* Simulated recoverable parse error. */
     if (strlen(name) > 4) {
         free(b->name);      /* release the name on the recoverable error path */
+        b->name = NULL;     /* object no longer owns a name buffer */
         b->size = 0;
         return b;           /* hand the partially-initialised blob back */
     }
```
A slightly stronger local cleanup is to centralize destruction even on the partial path:
```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    free(b->name);
    b->name = NULL;
    b->size = 0;
    return b;
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Define and enforce a single ownership/state invariant for `blob_t`: any live `blob_t` returned to callers must either own a valid `name` pointer or have `name == NULL`; no live object may contain a dangling pointer. Structurally, avoid returning ambiguous partially initialized objects: make `load_blob` return a status code and initialize an output `blob_t` only on success, or introduce a dedicated `blob_init`/`blob_destroy` API that zero-initializes fields and uses one cleanup path. For example:
```c
typedef enum { BLOB_OK, BLOB_RECOVERABLE_EMPTY, BLOB_OOM } blob_status;

static blob_status load_blob(const char *name, blob_t *out) {
    *out = (blob_t){ .name = NULL, .size = 0 };
    char *tmp = strdup(name);
    if (!tmp) return BLOB_OOM;

    if (strlen(name) > 4) {
        free(tmp);
        return BLOB_RECOVERABLE_EMPTY;
    }

    out->name = tmp;
    out->size = strlen(tmp);
    return BLOB_OK;
}
```
This makes ownership explicit, keeps partially initialized storage destructor-safe, and prevents this class of double-free bugs caused by stale owning pointers.

